Question 9
What are getters and setters in LWC? How are they useful?
Companies that asked this: TCS, Salesforce, Infosys, Accenture, Capgemini, IBM, Microsoft

Answer:
Getters:

Read-only computed properties

Automatically reactive â€” recalculates when dependent data changes

Used for dynamic logic, formatting, or conditional rendering

Cached until dependencies change (performance benefit)

get fullName() {
    return `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`;
}
 
get isFormValid() {
    return this.email && this.firstName && this.lastName;
}
 
// CSS class computation
get buttonClass() {
    return this.isFormValid ? 'enabled' : 'disabled';
}
Setters:

Property validation - Validate data before assignment

Side effects - Trigger actions when property changes

Data transformation - Modify data during assignment

Common with @api for public property control

// @api property with validation
_recordId;
 
@api
get recordId() {
    return this._recordId;
}
 
set recordId(value) {
    if (value && value.length === 18) {
        this._recordId = value;
        this.loadData(); // Side effect
    }
}
 
// Data transformation
set userInput(value) {
    this._userInput = value.trim().toLowerCase();
}
html

<template>
    <h2>Welcome, {fullName}!</h2>
    <button class={buttonClass} disabled={isFormValid}>Submit</button>
</template>


Interview Tips:

Emphasize @api patterns - Show validation with public properties

Mention template integration - How getters appear in HTML

Performance benefits - Getters cached until dependencies change

Real examples - Form validation, computed styles, side effects
